#compdef devd
# =============================================================================
# devd — Aldo Cortesi's "local webserver for developers" — a
#        compact static-file HTTP server with built-in livereload,
#        TLS auto-cert generation, request/response logging, and
#        upload/download throttling.  Designed as the local-dev
#        sibling of Cortesi's `modd` (file-watcher + command-
#        runner) — the typical workflow is `modd → devd` where
#        modd watches source files, rebuilds output, and notifies
#        devd to push livereload events to connected browsers.
#        devd's distinguishing features:
#          - Auto-pick a sensible port (no manual -p needed)
#          - Auto-generated self-signed TLS certs at ~/.devd.cert
#          - Per-route mappings: [SUBDOMAIN]/<PATH>=<DIR> or
#            [SUBDOMAIN]/<PATH>=<URL> for reverse-proxying
#          - Livereload via WebSocket — browser auto-refreshes
#            when a watched path changes
#          - Bandwidth throttling (--down/--up KBps) and latency
#            injection (--latency ms) for simulating slow networks
#          - HTTP basic auth (--password USER:PASS)
#          - CORS-allow-everything mode (--crossdomain) for
#            front-end-only API testing
#        Compact, batteries-included alternative to `serve` /
#        `http-server` / `python -m http.server`, with developer-
#        friendly features (livereload, TLS, throttling) that
#        the simpler servers lack.
#
# Author:  Aldo Cortesi — Australian security researcher and
#          developer-tools author best known for `mitmproxy`
#          (the de-facto Python TLS-interception toolkit, ~36k
#          GitHub stars).  Cortesi's Go-side projects:
#          `devd` (local webserver, 3.4k stars), `modd`
#          (file-watcher + cmd-runner, 1.6k stars), `termlog`
#          (terminal logging library used by both).  These tools
#          share design DNA: small, focused, opinionated; emit
#          colored structured logs to stdout; chain together
#          through filesystem signals.
# Source:  https://github.com/cortesi/devd
#          https://github.com/cortesi/devd/blob/master/cmd/devd/devd.go
# CLI:     cmd/devd/devd.go — uses `gopkg.in/alecthomas/kingpin.v2`
#          via fluent builder pattern: every flag is declared
#          with `kingpin.Flag(name, help).Short(c).Default(d).
#          PlaceHolder(p).<TypeConstructor>()`.
# Library: alecthomas/kingpin (v2)
#          ("A Go CLI library with fluent builder + struct-tag
#           support" — Alec Thomas — released 2014 as a successor
#           to the limitations of stdlib `flag`, with FLUENT-
#           BUILDER syntax that lets each flag chain its
#           constraints — short form, default, placeholder, type,
#           required-ness, env-var binding — in a single
#           expression.  Kingpin became the de-facto standard
#           for Prometheus and many Go infrastructure tools
#           before alecthomas/kong (Kingpin's struct-tag-based
#           successor) took over for new projects in 2019+.)
# License: MIT (devd); MIT (kingpin)
# Status:  devd — last active release (cortesi/devd) marked
#          "archived 2023" on GitHub but binaries remain widely
#          installed; kingpin v2 — maintenance mode but still
#          updated periodically.  alecthomas/kong is the
#          spiritual successor and is heavily used today.
#          Kingpin v2 remains in use across ~thousands of Go
#          projects including Prometheus / Alertmanager
#          (`amtool`) / older Telegraf / mitmproxy-side tooling.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — GO CROSSES TO 49
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 49TH Go CLI library variant.  Go climbs from 48 to 49 documented
# libraries (alecthomas/kingpin v2 via devd).  New leaderboard:
# Rust=49, Go=49, TypeScript-Node=48 (Rust+Go TWO-WAY TIE AT 49 —
# the ninth two-way tie at 48-or-above of this round-sequence).
# Taxonomy now spans 306 cross-language CLI library variants across
# 74 documented languages.
#
# Pattern: 1 new language (R565 Seed7) → R566 Rust=49 (color-eyre) →
# R567 Go=49 (kingpin THIS) → expected R568 TS-Node=49.  This is
# the 2nd of 3 leader bumps in the current segment.
#
# This completion EXPANDS Axis 1 (ARGV PARSING) within Go.  Go now
# has DOCUMENTED Go argv parsers spanning:
#   - Stdlib `flag`
#   - jessevdk/go-flags
#   - alexflint/go-arg
#   - DavidGamba/go-getoptions
#   - alecthomas/kong (struct-tag descendant of kingpin)
#   - akamensky/argparse
#   - mkideal/cli
#   - jawher/mow.cli
#   - jpillora/opts
#   - teris-io/cli
#   - leaanthony/clir
#   - rsc.io/getopt
#   - thatisuday/commando
#   - google/subcommands
#   - projectdiscovery/goflags (R563)
#   - spf13/cobra, urfave/cli, spf13/pflag (used elsewhere)
#   - alecthomas/kingpin (R567, THIS)
#
# kingpin is DISTINCT from every other documented Go argv parser by
# being a FLUENT BUILDER WITH METHOD CHAINING — every flag is
# declared with a chain of constructor-style methods that
# successively narrow the flag's type, defaults, validation, and
# documentation.  Compare:
#   * Stdlib flag: imperative `flag.StringVar(&v, "name", "def", "help")`
#   * cobra/pflag: per-command struct + `cmd.Flags().StringP(...)`
#   * urfave/cli: slice of `cli.Flag{Name, Usage, Value, ...}` structs
#   * kong: struct-tag-based (struct field tags carry flag specs)
#   * kingpin: METHOD-CHAINED BUILDER — each flag is one
#               expression with all attributes in fluent chain
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS kingpin AND WHY IS IT THE 49TH GO CLI LIBRARY?
#
# kingpin (https://github.com/alecthomas/kingpin, 3500+ stars) is
# **Alec Thomas's "Go CLI library with fluent builder + struct-tag
# support"** — a Go argv parser released 2014 that introduced the
# FLUENT-BUILDER pattern to Go CLI design.  Kingpin became
# Prometheus's standard CLI library and was used by `amtool` (the
# Alertmanager CLI), Telegraf, mitmproxy-go-side tools, and many
# other infrastructure utilities.
#
# kingpin's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. FLUENT-BUILDER METHOD-CHAINED FLAG DECLARATION — Every
#      flag is one expression that chains attribute methods:
#
#          var (
#              addr = kingpin.Flag("address", "Address to listen on").
#                  Short('A').
#                  Default("127.0.0.1").
#                  String()
#
#              port = kingpin.Flag("port", "Port to listen on").
#                  Short('p').
#                  Required().
#                  Int()
#
#              cert = kingpin.Flag("cert", "Certificate bundle file").
#                  Short('c').
#                  PlaceHolder("PATH").
#                  ExistingFile()
#
#              latency = kingpin.Flag("latency", "Add N ms latency").
#                  PlaceHolder("N").
#                  Short('n').
#                  Default("0").
#                  Int()
#          )
#
#      The final method in the chain (.String() / .Int() /
#      .ExistingFile() / .Bool() / .Uint() / .Strings() / etc)
#      determines the flag's TYPE and returns a *T pointer.
#      Compare:
#         * Go stdlib flag: `flag.StringVar(&v, ...)` — 4 args
#         * cobra: `cmd.Flags().StringVarP(&v, "name", "n", "default", "help")` — 5 args
#         * kong: `struct { Addr string `kong:"default='127.0.0.1'"` }`
#         * kingpin: `kingpin.Flag(...).Default(...).Short(...).String()`
#                    — fluent chain, attribute order flexible
#      FIRST documented Go argv parser with chainable fluent-
#      builder + return-type-determines-flag-type semantics.
#
#   2. TYPE-CONSTRUCTOR METHODS DETERMINE FLAG TYPE — Where
#      stdlib flag uses separate functions per type (StringVar,
#      IntVar, BoolVar), kingpin uses METHODS on the
#      FlagClause builder that BOTH determine type AND return
#      the result pointer:
#
#          .String()          → *string
#          .Int()             → *int
#          .Uint()            → *uint
#          .Bool()            → *bool
#          .Float64()         → *float64
#          .Duration()        → *time.Duration
#          .IP()              → *net.IP
#          .Strings()         → *[]string  (repeated --flag accumulates)
#          .Ints()            → *[]int
#          .ExistingFile()    → *string (validates file exists)
#          .ExistingFiles()   → *[]string
#          .ExistingDir()     → *string (validates directory exists)
#          .Counter()         → *int (count -v -v -v as 3)
#          .Enum("a","b","c") → *string (constrained to enum)
#          .HintAction(fn)    → *string (with completion hint)
#
#      Compare:
#         * Go stdlib flag: type-specific functions (StringVar, IntVar)
#         * cobra/pflag: type-specific functions (StringVar, IntVar)
#         * kong: type derived from struct field's Go type
#         * kingpin: type-constructor methods chained at end of
#                    fluent-builder, with rich variety including
#                    ExistingFile/Counter/Enum/HintAction
#      FIRST documented Go argv parser with type-constructor-
#      method-chain pattern (vs type-specific top-level funcs).
#
#   3. STRUCT-TAG SUPPORT (kingpin v2.2+) — kingpin v2 added
#      OPTIONAL struct-tag-based declaration in addition to the
#      fluent builder.  Pass a struct to kingpin with
#      `kingpin.StructFromTags(...)` and tags drive everything:
#
#          type Config struct {
#              Address  string `help:"Address to listen on" short:"A" default:"127.0.0.1"`
#              Port     int    `help:"Port to listen on" short:"p" required:"true"`
#              CertFile string `help:"Cert bundle" short:"c" type:"existingfile"`
#          }
#
#      Compare:
#         * cobra: no native struct-tag support; people add
#                   reflection wrappers
#         * urfave/cli: no struct-tag support
#         * kong: struct-tags are PRIMARY mode (no fluent builder)
#         * kingpin: SUPPORTS BOTH fluent builder AND struct-tags
#      FIRST documented Go argv parser with DUAL fluent-builder +
#      struct-tag declaration modes (vs single mode).
#
#   4. AUTO-MAN-PAGE + AUTO-COMPLETION GENERATION — kingpin can
#      auto-generate a Unix man page from the same definitions
#      that drive runtime parsing, and ships with built-in shell-
#      completion generation for bash/zsh/fish.  Compare:
#         * Go stdlib flag: no man-page / no completion
#         * cobra: shell-completion via `cobra-cli completion`
#                   subcommand; man-page via cobra plugin
#         * urfave/cli: optional completion via app.EnableBashCompletion
#         * kingpin: BUILT-IN man-page + completion generation
#                    from the same FlagClause definitions used
#                    at runtime — single source of truth
#      FIRST documented Go argv parser with built-in single-
#      source-of-truth man-page + completion generation (vs
#      separate subcommand / plugin).
#
#   5. PROMETHEUS-ECOSYSTEM PROVENANCE — kingpin is the canonical
#      CLI library for the Prometheus monitoring stack
#      (alertmanager / amtool / pushgateway / various exporters)
#      and was the default choice for new infrastructure Go tools
#      from 2015-2019.  Major users:
#         * Prometheus alertmanager (`amtool`)
#         * Prometheus pushgateway
#         * blackbox_exporter
#         * snmp_exporter
#         * node_exporter (some versions)
#         * mtail (Google's log mining tool)
#         * mitmproxy's go-side tools
#         * devd (THIS — local webserver)
#         * modd (file-watcher + cmd-runner)
#         * Many Go observability tools
#      Compare every other documented Go argv parser — kong is
#      kingpin's spiritual successor with struct-tag-only API
#      (kong came out 2019 by the same author).  cobra dominates
#      kubernetes ecosystem.  kingpin dominates Prometheus-era
#      observability tooling.  FIRST documented Go argv parser
#      with Prometheus-ecosystem provenance.
#
# kingpin's relationship to other documented Go CLI libraries:
#
#   * Like alecthomas/kong (undocumented as headline) — same author,
#       successor design.  kong = struct-tag-only; kingpin =
#       fluent-builder + struct-tag.
#   * Like spf13/cobra — heavy CLI framework with subcommands,
#       completion, help text.  kingpin focuses on flag fluency;
#       cobra focuses on subcommand-tree management.
#   * Like urfave/cli — both have struct-based mode.  kingpin's
#       fluent builder is unique; urfave is struct-only.
#   * Like Go stdlib flag — both expose pointers as the result of
#       declaration.  kingpin extends with chained constraints,
#       type-constructor methods, struct-tag mode, man-page +
#       completion generation.
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Rust:    clap_builder fluent API (clap v3 builder) —
#                     similar chained-builder pattern with method
#                     chaining; clap derive uses struct tags
#                     similar to kingpin's struct mode
#         * TS-Node: chai-test-style chained API (yargs chains
#                     `.option(...).option(...).version(...)`)
#                     close in spirit, but yargs returns the
#                     builder rather than per-flag pointers
#     kingpin is the FIRST documented argv parser combining
#     fluent-builder + struct-tag + type-constructor-method-chain
#     + man-page-generation in one library.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE devd CLI — kingpin v2 fluent-builder + kingpin.Parse()
#
# devd's argv definitions all use `kingpin.Flag(name, help)` chains:
#
#     import "gopkg.in/alecthomas/kingpin.v2"
#
#     func main() {
#         address := kingpin.Flag("address", "Address to listen on").
#             Short('A').Default("127.0.0.1").String()
#
#         certFile := kingpin.Flag("cert", "Certificate bundle - enables TLS").
#             Short('c').PlaceHolder("PATH").ExistingFile()
#
#         downKbps := kingpin.Flag("down", "Throttle downstream kBps").
#             PlaceHolder("N").Short('d').Default("0").Uint()
#
#         routes := kingpin.Arg("route", "Route mappings").Required().Strings()
#
#         kingpin.CommandLine.HelpFlag.Short('h')
#         kingpin.Version(devd.Version)
#         kingpin.Parse()
#         // ...use *address, *certFile, *downKbps, *routes...
#     }
#
# Routes are positional arguments with these forms:
#
#     [SUBDOMAIN]/<PATH>=<DIR>      # mount DIR under PATH (optionally
#                                   # under SUBDOMAIN subdomain)
#     [SUBDOMAIN]/<PATH>=<URL>      # reverse-proxy PATH to URL
#     <DIR>                         # serve DIR at root
#     <URL>                         # reverse-proxy root to URL
#
# Five-axis distinctness from every other documented Go CLI parser:
#
#   1. FLUENT-BUILDER METHOD CHAINING — Every other documented Go
#      argv parser uses either imperative declaration (stdlib
#      flag, cobra), struct-based slice declaration (urfave/cli),
#      or struct-tag declaration (kong).  kingpin uses fluent-
#      builder method chaining where each flag is one expression
#      with all attributes in a chain.  FIRST documented Go argv
#      parser with this pattern.
#
#   2. TYPE-CONSTRUCTOR METHODS (.String() / .Int() / etc) — Every
#      other documented Go argv parser uses type-specific top-
#      level functions (StringVar/IntVar) or struct fields with
#      Go types.  kingpin's type-constructor methods at the end
#      of each chain determine flag type AND return the result
#      pointer.  Rich type catalog includes ExistingFile/Counter/
#      Enum/HintAction.  FIRST documented Go argv parser with
#      this pattern.
#
#   3. DUAL FLUENT-BUILDER + STRUCT-TAG MODES — kingpin v2 added
#      struct-tag declaration alongside the original fluent
#      builder.  Every other documented Go argv parser uses ONLY
#      ONE declaration mode.  FIRST documented Go argv parser
#      with dual declaration modes.
#
#   4. BUILT-IN MAN-PAGE + SHELL-COMPLETION GENERATION — Every
#      other documented Go argv parser either lacks these
#      generators or requires separate subcommands/plugins.
#      kingpin has BUILT-IN single-source-of-truth generation
#      from the same FlagClause definitions.  FIRST documented
#      Go argv parser with built-in single-source-of-truth
#      generators.
#
#   5. PROMETHEUS-ECOSYSTEM PROVENANCE — Every other documented
#      Go argv parser is either general-purpose (cobra/urfave/
#      cli/flag) or has different ecosystem provenance (goflags =
#      ProjectDiscovery security tools).  kingpin is the
#      canonical Prometheus-stack CLI library — alertmanager,
#      amtool, pushgateway, exporters, mtail, etc all use it.
#      FIRST documented Go argv parser with Prometheus-stack
#      provenance.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/cortesi/devd/blob/master/cmd/devd/devd.go
# main() function — every kingpin.Flag chain is reproduced below.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -s -S \
    '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
    '--help-long[show long help]' \
    '--help-man[generate man page]' \
    '--version[show version]' \
    '(-A --address)'{-A,--address=}'[address to listen on]:address:_hosts' \
    '(-a --all)'{-a,--all}'[listen on all addresses]' \
    '(-c --cert)'{-c,--cert=}'[certificate bundle file (enables TLS)]:file:_files' \
    '(-C --color)'{-C,--color}'[force color output]' \
    '(-d --down)'{-d,--down=}'[throttle downstream from client (kBps)]:N:' \
    '(-f --notfound)'{-f,--notfound=}'[default file/path when static file is not found]:path:_files' \
    '*'{-f,--notfound=}'[default file/path when static file is not found (repeatable)]:path:_files' \
    '(-H --logheaders)'{-H,--logheaders}'[log headers]' \
    '*'{-I,--ignore=}'[disable logging for requests matching regex (host/path)]:regex:' \
    '(-L --livereload)'{-L,--livereload}'[enable livereload]' \
    '(-l --livewatch)'{-l,--livewatch}'[enable livereload and watch for static-file changes]' \
    '(-m --modd)'{-m,--modd}'[modd is parent (synonym for -LCt)]' \
    '(-n --latency)'{-n,--latency=}'[add N ms of round-trip latency]:N:' \
    '(-o --open)'{-o,--open}'[open browser window on startup]' \
    '(-p --port)'{-p,--port=}'[listen port (auto-pick if unset)]:port:' \
    '(-P --password)'{-P,--password=}'[HTTP basic auth USER:PASS]:user:pass:' \
    '(-q --quiet)'{-q,--quiet}'[silence all logs]' \
    '(-s --tls)'{-s,--tls}'[serve TLS with auto-generated self-signed cert (~/.devd.cert)]' \
    '(-t --notimestamps)'{-t,--notimestamps}'[disable timestamps in output]' \
    '(-T --logtime)'{-T,--logtime}'[log timing]' \
    '(-u --up)'{-u,--up=}'[throttle upstream from client (kBps)]:N:' \
    '*'{-w,--watch=}'[watch path to trigger livereload]:path:_files' \
    '(-X --crossdomain)'{-X,--crossdomain}'[set CORS headers to allow everything]' \
    '*'{-x,--exclude=}'[glob pattern for files to exclude from livereload]:pattern:' \
    '--debug[enable devd development debugging]' \
    '--completion-script-bash[output bash completion script]' \
    '--completion-script-zsh[output zsh completion script]' \
    '*: :->route' \
    && ret=0

case $state in
    route)
        _message '[SUBDOMAIN]/<PATH>=<DIR> | [SUBDOMAIN]/<PATH>=<URL> | <DIR> | <URL>'
        _files -/
        _urls
        ret=0
        ;;
esac

return ret
